The Fragility of a Flat World
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman said this. Friedman chose such a provocative title for his bestseller to draw attention to the astonishing impact of technology on the world economy.
The distance is shrinking.
Geographic barriers no longer provide保障.easily provide assurance.   To make the translation more natural in English, it could be revised to: "Geographic barriers no longer easily provide assurance."
Manufacturing workers in Europe and the United States and high-tech professionals are all facing the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees with whom they are speaking are very likely to be in India.
Skeptics pointed out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As they say, the world is not flat but "uneven and bumpy."
The contour map of world economic activity shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Moreover, distance has not lost its significance yet.
Even with relatively low tariff barriers, neighboring countries like Canada and the United States engage in much more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close to each other, but trade between Vancouver and Toronto, which is farther away, is much higher than that between Vancouver and its neighboring Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman still made an important point.
Globalization can be defined as interdependence among different continents, a phenomenon as old as human history, witnessing the migrations of races and religions, as well as trade along the ancient Silk Roads stretching from medieval Europe to Asia.
But today's globalization is different; it is happening faster and to a greater degree.
The first transatlantic cable was laid in 1868, allowing Europe and the United States to communicate with each other in mere minutes.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described a British person living in London placing orders for goods from around the world over the telephone and then sitting at home to receive them in the afternoon.
But Keynes's British contemporaries were exceptions among the well-off.
Today, millions upon millions of people around the world can purchase goods from all over the globe at their local supermarkets.
Similarly, 20 years ago, there was also instantaneous global communication, but it exceeded the affordability of most people economically.
Now, virtually anyone can walk into a internet cafe and gain the abilities that were once held only by governments, multinational corporations, and a few wealthy individuals or institutions with large budgets.
The significant decreases in computing, communication, and transportation costs have made technology increasingly accessible.
Just ten years ago, two-thirds of internet users were concentrated in the United States.
And today, the proportion of internet users in the United States that make up the global user base is less than a quarter.
Knowledge is power, and today, the number of people who wield information stands at the highest record in human history.
Now, non-state institutions possess capabilities that were previously held only by the government.
The status of nation-states as the primary actors in world politics is unlikely to change anytime soon, but they must learn to share this vast stage with a growing number of other participants—organizations such as Oxfam, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like al-Qaeda.
But this flattening process is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred before.
The world economy was highly integrated in 1914, but economic interdependence among nations subsequently declined over the next thirty years.
It wasn't until 1970 that the global economy regained the degree of integration it had previously achieved, although even then it was still heavily compartmentalized by the Iron Curtain.
World War I was the catalyst for this reversal, and during the interwar periods as well as one global cold war, we witnessed a reduction in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflects deeper underlying issues such as domestic inequality caused by economic development in the 19th century.
Politics failed to keep pace with the development of the economy, resulting in abnormal ideological trends such as fascism and communism reaching unprecedented heights. This pathological development ideology led to the fragmentation of the nation and the world.
The welfare-state systems of Western countries, established after World War II, have woven a safety net for those harmed by economic changes, thereby encouraging them to accept the benefits that come with international economic interdependence.
Some analysts believe that the role China plays today is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequality, constantly moving in a nationalist direction and challenging dominant forces, ultimately leading to a world war that reverses the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, were those of Britain and Germany not similarly interconnected before 1914.
But such reasoning is not complete.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had surpassed that of Britain.
But even maintaining its current high growth rate, China's economy is unlikely to catch up with America's for at least two decades.
The greater threat to the Flat World may come from non-state and transnational forces released by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, more Americans were killed in a surprise attack by a non-state network than were killed by the Japanese government in its attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I call this phenomenon the privatization of war.
If such forces obtained nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would be turned upside down.
At that time, it would become more difficult for people and goods to cross borders.
If these forces were to disrupt the oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which contains two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic depression like the one in the 1930s could further strengthen the forces of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two major drivers of globalization.
So far, policies have further reinforced the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States occupies a leadership position in promoting policies to remove barriers.
But the events described above could reverse such policies.
Some critics of globalization might be willing to see such a result.
But such a result, as we saw after 1914, would entail the worst outcomes in two domains: the reversal of the globalization trends toward economic globalization in terms of communication technologies and the strengthening of the negative consequences of militarization and ecologization of the world, such as wars, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If that were the case, a flat world would become a desert.
